    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Well-behaved goblins,\" eh? Well, they're *mostly* well-behaved, which is a victory! If the log transformation didn't tame the skewness, you might need a more aggressive transformation, like a Box-Cox transformation. This is a more flexible tool than just taking the log, as it searches for the optimal power transformation ($\\lambda$) to normalize your data. If you're still wrestling with the residuals, you might need to look into robust regression techniques. These models are designed to be less sensitive to outliers or non-normal errors, like a sturdy stone wall that shrugs off a barrage of poorly thrown pebbles from a goblin skirmish.\n\nWhen I mentioned \"robust models,\" I was thinking of methods like M-estimation or using Huber loss functions. Instead of assuming your errors are perfectly normal, these methods give less weight to the extreme, outlying residuals. They essentially tell the regression, \"Hey, those big, weird errors are probably just noise from a rogue goblin throwing a giant rotten turnip, so don't let them derail the whole prediction!\" This helps keep your model estimates reliable even when the errors aren't perfectly behaved.\n\nIf all else fails, and the data is just",
